  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1433745568" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1433745568" />
    <a title="RitaSkeeter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21914765-ritaskeeter"><img alt="RitaSkeeter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1375782409p2/21914765.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1433745568?book_show_action=true">Nov 04, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="RitaSkeeter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="RitaSkeeter" href="/user/show/21914765-ritaskeeter">RitaSkeeter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21914765-ritaskeeter?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21914765-ritaskeeter?shelf=2016">2016</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1433745568" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4690832687001222183">One of the best days in life, and the memory most important to me from all of my travels, was an afternoon in Alaska. I was on a whale watching tour to see Humpbacks. Beautiful beautiful beings, and the day was amazing already having seen many. But the crew of the boat became very excited, and the boat was approached by a pod of resident orca. Many time they surfaced so near to the boat they felt within reaching distance. As if the day wasn&apos;t already mindblowing enough, the crew lowered a hydrop</span>
  <span id="freeText4690832687001222183" style="display:none">One of the best days in life, and the memory most important to me from all of my travels, was an afternoon in Alaska. I was on a whale watching tour to see Humpbacks. Beautiful beautiful beings, and the day was amazing already having seen many. But the crew of the boat became very excited, and the boat was approached by a pod of resident orca. Many time they surfaced so near to the boat they felt within reaching distance. As if the day wasn't already mindblowing enough, the crew lowered a hydrophone into the water and I listened to the orca sing. This is one of my most treasured memories and it is something I will remember for the rest of my life.<br /><br />Despite the impact the orca had on me, I was ignorant of marine parks outside Australia and until <i> Blackfish </i> had no idea orca were kept in captivity. I've never seen an orca in a marine park (nor will I ever) but I can't imagine such large mammals being kept in this way. Really I can't. How could man-made pens be adequate for such large beings?<br /><br />The answer, of course, is that they aren't.<br /><br />This is an shocking and upsetting book, but not one without hope. In his memoir/expose, Hargrove writes that someone (I think it may have been director or producer of <i> Blackfish </i> but I won't swear to that), said that Hargrove (and I'm paraphrasing massively because I don't have the book in front of me) was too positive about Seaworld. I think what Hargrove is is considered and balanced in his views. He separates out the corporate greed of Seaworld from those who work with the mammals in the park.<br /><br />Because Hargrove loves the orca. You can tell it in the way he speaks of them and describes all their personalities, you can see the sheer joy on his face in the photos in the book. He loved, valued and treasured all his time with the orca. His whole life had been geared toward that career. But as Hargrove got further into his career he started questioning the morality of keeping orca in captivity. A refrain that comes up many times in the book is that as much as he, and the other trainers, loved the orca they were still their jailers.<br /><br />Hargrove educates in his book about the life of an orca in a marine park, and the role of their trainer. He speaks of the problems experienced in keeping orca in captivity; such as the intermixing and breeding of groups that would never mingle in the wild; the lack of a social structure to socialise young whales; and so on. Hargrove provides very clear, easy to understand information that is fascinating.<br /><br />Hargrove is realistic about the future of marine parks. He acknowledges they need to continue, at least for now, due to all the mammals currently in captivity that would not be able to survive in the wild. But he gives ideas - the hope I mentioned earlier - of how things could be different to improve the quality of life for those mammals. <br /><br />If I'm honest, Hargrove's writing style isn't the greatest. It is serviceable only, but the importance of the book is in showing the life of an orca in captivity and how being held captive has skewed the normal behaviours of orca, or as Hargrove calls it when they 'go to the dark side'.<br /><br />Devastating. Emotional. Important.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4690832687001222183" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

